<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 microid-mailto+http:sha1:efd7b59bb380d9d2a84b271f547ed85f78df875d" id="li-comment-55533">
<div id="comment-55533">
<div class="comment-author">
Lyda @ <a href='http://lydaclark.blogspot.com' rel='external' target='_blank'>lydaclark.blogspot.com</a></div>
<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.elanaspantry.com/peppermint-patties/#comment-55533">December 9, 2011 at 11:55 am</a></div>
<p>I just made peppermint chocolates based on this recipe on my blog <a target="_blank" href="http://lydaclark.blogspot.com/2011/12/festive-peppermint-chocolates.html" rel="nofollow">http://lydaclark.blogspot.com/2011/12/festive-peppermint-chocolates.html</a> I didn't have peppermint oil on hand so I used crushed up peppermint candy, which actually turned out really well. I think the key to keeping the coconut oil from melting and get the chocolate to stick to it is making sure the melted chocolate is closer to room temperature. I melted it and let it sit out for a few minutes. I also left everything in the freezer for much longer. Turned out amazing!</p>
